    {"id": "EI010", "section": "Electronics Information", "topic": "Series Circuits", "question_text": "Three resistors of 4Ω, 6Ω, and 10Ω are connected in series. What is the total resistance?", "options": ["2.0Ω", "6.67Ω", "20Ω", "240Ω"], "correct_index": 2, "difficulty": 1, "explanation": "In series: R_total = R1 + R2 + R3 = 4 + 6 + 10 = 20Ω. Total resistance in series always increases — it equals the sum of all resistors.", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "EI011", "section": "Electronics Information", "topic": "Series Circuits", "question_text": "In a series circuit with a 12V battery and three equal resistors, how does the voltage distribute?", "options": ["All 12V drops across the first resistor", "12V distributes equally across all three", "Each resistor gets 12V", "Voltage does not change in a series circuit"], "correct_index": 1, "difficulty": 2, "explanation": "In a series circuit, the total voltage divides across the resistors in proportion to their resistance. For three equal resistors, 12V ÷ 3 = 4V across each. Total voltage = sum of all drops.", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "EI012", "section": "Electronics Information", "topic": "Series Circuits", "question_text": "If one bulb burns out in a series circuit of three bulbs, what happens?", "options": ["The other two bulbs get brighter", "The other two bulbs stay the same", "The other two bulbs go out too", "Only one remaining bulb goes out"], "correct_index": 2, "difficulty": 1, "explanation": "In a series circuit, current has only one path. If one component fails (open circuit), the circuit is broken and no current flows — all components stop working. Old Christmas lights wired in series had this problem.", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},

