    {"id": "EI052", "section": "Electronics Information", "topic": "Diodes", "question_text": "Which type of diode emits light when forward biased?", "options": ["Zener diode", "Rectifier diode", "LED (light-emitting diode)", "Photodiode"], "correct_index": 2, "difficulty": 1, "explanation": "An LED (Light-Emitting Diode) emits light when forward biased. Zener diodes are used for voltage regulation. Photodiodes generate current when exposed to light (the reverse of an LED).", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "EI053", "section": "Electronics Information", "topic": "Power", "question_text": "A device rated at 60W operating at 120V draws how much current?", "options": ["0.5A", "2A", "7,200A", "60A"], "correct_index": 0, "difficulty": 2, "explanation": "I = P/V = 60W / 120V = 0.5A. A standard light bulb drawing only half an amp explains why many appliances can share a household circuit (which typically handles 15-20A).", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "EI054", "section": "Electronics Information", "topic": "Ohm's Law", "question_text": "What happens to current in a circuit if resistance is increased while voltage stays constant?", "options": ["Current increases", "Current stays the same", "Current decreases", "Current reverses direction"], "correct_index": 2, "difficulty": 1, "explanation": "From Ohm's Law, I = V/R. If R increases and V is constant, I decreases. Resistance and current are inversely proportional (when voltage is constant).", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "EI055", "section": "Electronics Information", "topic": "Transformers", "question_text": "Why is electrical power transmitted at high voltage over long distances?", "options": ["High voltage charges batteries faster", "High voltage reduces current, which reduces power loss in wires (P=I²R)", "High voltage increases wire conductivity", "Transformers only work with high voltage"], "correct_index": 1, "difficulty": 3, "explanation": "Power loss in transmission lines is P_loss = I²R. Transmitting at high voltage reduces current (P = VI, same power but higher V means lower I), dramatically reducing I²R losses. Step-up transformers raise voltage for transmission; step-down transformers reduce it for homes.", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "EI056", "section": "Electronics Information", "topic": "Transistors", "question_text": "In digital electronics, a transistor acting as a switch is either:", "options": ["Partially on or partially off", "Fully on (saturated) or fully off (cut off)", "Slowly transitioning between states", "Responding only to AC signals"], "correct_index": 1, "difficulty": 2, "explanation": "Digital transistors are binary — fully on (saturated, maximum current, low voltage = logic 0 at output) or fully off (cut off, no current, high voltage = logic 1). Billions of these switches form modern processors.", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "EI057", "section": "Electronics Information", "topic": "Basic Concepts", "question_text": "Grounding a circuit provides:", "options": ["Additional power to the circuit", "A safe path for excess current to flow to Earth", "A resistance reference point", "Higher current capacity"], "correct_index": 1, "difficulty": 2, "explanation": "Grounding provides a safe return path for fault currents (like if a hot wire touches a metal case). The ground wire directs fault current to Earth, tripping the breaker/fuse rather than shocking a person who touches the device.", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "EI058", "section": "Electronics Information", "topic": "AC vs DC", "question_text": "Most consumer electronics (phones, computers) internally operate on:", "options": ["High-voltage AC", "Low-voltage DC", "High-frequency AC", "Variable DC"], "correct_index": 1, "difficulty": 2, "explanation": "Internal electronics (processors, memory, sensors) require low-voltage DC (typically 3.3V, 5V, or 12V). Power adapters/chargers convert household AC to low-voltage DC for devices.", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "EI059", "section": "Electronics Information", "topic": "Capacitors", "question_text": "One common use of capacitors in power supply circuits is to:", "options": ["Increase voltage", "Reduce resistance", "Smooth out voltage fluctuations (filter ripple)", "Convert DC to AC"], "correct_index": 2, "difficulty": 2, "explanation": "After a rectifier converts AC to pulsating DC, capacitors smooth the voltage by charging during peaks and discharging during troughs. This 'filter' produces steady DC. This is in every phone charger.", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "EI060", "section": "Electronics Information", "topic": "Inductors", "question_text": "An inductor's opposition to AC current is called:", "options": ["Resistance", "Capacitance", "Inductive reactance", "Impedance"], "correct_index": 2, "difficulty": 3, "explanation": "An inductor opposes changes in current. Its opposition to AC is called inductive reactance (XL = 2πfL, measured in ohms). Unlike resistance, reactance varies with frequency. Total AC opposition is impedance (Z).", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "EI061", "section": "Electronics Information", "topic": "Fuses and Breakers", "question_text": "If you replace a 15-amp fuse with a 30-amp fuse, the risk is:", "options": ["The circuit will run more efficiently", "The fuse will blow immediately", "Wiring can overheat and catch fire before the fuse blows", "Voltage in the circuit will increase"], "correct_index": 2, "difficulty": 2, "explanation": "Fuses must match the wire rating. A 30A fuse in a 15A-rated circuit allows twice the safe current to flow — the wiring can overheat and start a fire before the oversized fuse blows. Always match fuse size to wire rating.", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "EI062", "section": "Electronics Information", "topic": "Basic Concepts", "question_text": "A multimeter can measure all of the following EXCEPT:", "options": ["Voltage", "Current", "Resistance", "Inductance (directly)"], "correct_index": 3, "difficulty": 2, "explanation": "A standard multimeter measures voltage (V), current (A), and resistance (Ω). Measuring inductance directly requires a specialized LCR meter. Some advanced multimeters include capacitance measurement.", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "EI063", "section": "Electronics Information", "topic": "Series Circuits", "question_text": "In a series circuit with a 9V battery and three identical resistors, the voltage across each resistor is:", "options": ["9V", "3V", "27V", "1V"], "correct_index": 1, "difficulty": 1, "explanation": "In series, voltage divides equally among identical resistors. 9V ÷ 3 = 3V per resistor. The total voltage always equals the sum of individual voltage drops (Kirchhoff's Voltage Law).", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "EI064", "section": "Electronics Information", "topic": "Parallel Circuits", "question_text": "In a parallel circuit, if one branch is disconnected, the other branches:", "options": ["Also stop working", "Draw more current to compensate", "Continue working normally", "Have reduced voltage"], "correct_index": 2, "difficulty": 1, "explanation": "In parallel, each branch is independent. Disconnecting one branch does not affect others — they still receive full voltage. This is why household circuits are parallel: one device failing doesn't affect others.", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "EI065", "section": "Electronics Information", "topic": "Diodes", "question_text": "A Zener diode is commonly used for:", "options": ["Light emission", "Voltage regulation (maintaining a fixed voltage)", "Amplification", "Rectification only"], "correct_index": 1, "difficulty": 3, "explanation": "Zener diodes are designed to operate in reverse breakdown at a specific voltage (the Zener voltage). This makes them ideal for voltage regulation — they clamp voltage to a fixed value in a circuit.", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "EI066", "section": "Electronics Information", "topic": "Basic Concepts", "question_text": "Kirchhoff's Current Law states that:", "options": ["Voltage is the same at all points", "The sum of currents entering a junction equals the sum leaving it", "Resistance increases with temperature", "Power is conserved in a transformer"], "correct_index": 1, "difficulty": 3, "explanation": "Kirchhoff's Current Law (KCL): the total current entering any junction must equal the total current leaving it. This is a form of conservation of charge. It's used to analyze complex circuit junctions.", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "EI067", "section": "Electronics Information", "topic": "Basic Concepts", "question_text": "The function of a resistor in a circuit is to:", "options": ["Store electrical charge", "Oppose current flow and drop voltage", "Amplify the signal", "Convert AC to DC"], "correct_index": 1, "difficulty": 1, "explanation": "Resistors oppose current flow (consume/dissipate energy as heat) and create voltage drops. They are used to limit current, divide voltage, and set operating points for transistors.", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "EI068", "section": "Electronics Information", "topic": "AC vs DC", "question_text": "In an AC circuit, the voltage measured by a voltmeter reads:", "options": ["Peak voltage", "Average voltage (which is zero)", "RMS (root mean square) voltage", "Instantaneous voltage"], "correct_index": 2, "difficulty": 3, "explanation": "AC voltmeters read RMS (root mean square) voltage — the effective DC equivalent. US household 120V AC means 120V RMS; the actual peak voltage is about 170V. RMS is what matters for power calculations.", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "EI069", "section": "Electronics Information", "topic": "Transformers", "question_text": "A transformer with 500 primary turns and 50 secondary turns is a:", "options": ["Step-up transformer", "Step-down transformer", "Isolation transformer", "Frequency transformer"], "correct_index": 1, "difficulty": 2, "explanation": "More primary turns than secondary = step-down transformer (reduces voltage). The turns ratio is 10:1, so output voltage is 1/10 of input voltage. Step-up has more secondary turns than primary.", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "EI070", "section": "Electronics Information", "topic": "Power", "question_text": "Energy consumed by an appliance is measured in:", "options": ["Watts", "Amperes", "Kilowatt-hours", "Volts"], "correct_index": 2, "difficulty": 2, "explanation": "Energy = Power × Time. Kilowatt-hours (kWh) are used for billing energy consumption. Watts measure the rate of power use. A 1,000W (1 kW) appliance running for 1 hour uses 1 kWh of energy.", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "EI071", "section": "Electronics Information", "topic": "Conductors and Insulators", "question_text": "Why is copper used for electrical wiring instead of silver (a better conductor)?", "options": ["Copper has lower resistance than silver", "Copper is much less expensive while still being highly conductive", "Silver oxidizes too quickly", "Copper handles higher voltages"], "correct_index": 1, "difficulty": 2, "explanation": "Silver has slightly lower resistance but is far too expensive for widespread use. Copper offers an excellent balance of conductivity and cost, making it the standard for electrical wiring.", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "EI072", "section": "Electronics Information", "topic": "Capacitors", "question_text": "Which component would you use to block DC while allowing AC to pass?", "options": ["Resistor", "Inductor", "Capacitor", "Transformer"], "correct_index": 2, "difficulty": 2, "explanation": "A capacitor blocks DC (charges up and then no more current flows) but passes AC (the alternating voltage constantly charges/discharges it). This is called a coupling or blocking capacitor and is used in audio amplifiers.", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "EI073", "section": "Electronics Information", "topic": "Inductors", "question_text": "An inductor opposes high-frequency AC more than low-frequency AC because:", "options": ["Higher frequency means more voltage", "Inductive reactance (XL) increases with frequency (XL = 2πfL)", "Low frequency causes magnetic saturation", "High frequency heats the coil more"], "correct_index": 1, "difficulty": 3, "explanation": "Inductive reactance XL = 2πfL. As frequency (f) increases, XL increases. This means inductors block high frequencies more than low frequencies — the opposite of capacitors. This property is used in LC filters.", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "EI074", "section": "Electronics Information", "topic": "Basic Concepts", "question_text": "What does the abbreviation 'EMF' stand for in electronics?", "options": ["Electrical Measurement Force", "Electromagnetic Field", "Electromotive Force", "Electronic Modulation Factor"], "correct_index": 2, "difficulty": 2, "explanation": "EMF stands for Electromotive Force — the voltage generated by a source (battery, generator) that drives current through a circuit. Despite having 'force' in the name, EMF is measured in volts, not newtons.", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "EI075", "section": "Electronics Information", "topic": "Series vs Parallel", "question_text": "An ohmmeter measures resistance. To measure a resistor correctly, the resistor must be:", "options": ["Connected to the circuit while powered", "Removed from the circuit (disconnected)", "Connected in series with the power supply", "Measured while current is flowing"], "correct_index": 1, "difficulty": 2, "explanation": "To accurately measure resistance, the component must be disconnected from the circuit. If measured in-circuit, parallel paths and powered components give false readings. Always de-energize and isolate the component.", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
